 England":"Broadwater, Sussex, England","England":"England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1487–1533":"1487–1533","1480–1533":"1480–1533","1505–1522":"1505–1522","1510–Female":"1510–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1505–1599":"1505–1599","1510–1628":"1510–1628","1453–1508":"1453–1508","1455–Female":"1455–Deceased","12 Jun 1508":"12 June 1508","1480":"1480","about 1505":"about 1505","1533":"1533","1599":"1599","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","about 1504":"about 1504","1453":"1453","1508":"1508","1628":"1628","1505":"1505","St. Amands, Grandon Underwood, Wiltshire, England":"Spain","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Broadwater, Sussex, England":"Broadwater, Sussex, England","England":"England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Anthony","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual English form of the old Roman family name <i>Antonius</i>, which is of uncertain (probably Etruscan) origin. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> (not normally reflected in the pronunciation) represents a learned but erroneous attempt to associate it with Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. In the post-classical period it was a common name, borne by various early saints, most notably a 3rd-century Egyptian hermit monk, who is regarded as the founder of Christian monasticism."],"variants":[{"name":"Antony","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anthony ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Anthony Beauchamp was born in 1487, in Herefordshire, England, his father, Baron Richard Beauchamp, was 34 and his mother, Mary de Saint Amand Wroughton, was 33. He married Lady Anne West about 1504, in Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1533, in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 46, and was buried in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England."},"et":{"1487–1533":"1487–1533","1480–1533":"1480–1533","1505–1522":"1505–1522","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1505–1599":"1505–1599","1510–1628":"1510–1628","1453–1508":"1453–1508","1455–Female":"1455–Surnud","12 Jun 1508":"12. juuni 1508","1480":"1480","about 1505":"umbes 1505","1533":"1533","1599":"1599","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","about 1504":"umbes 1504","1453":"1453","1508":"1508","1628":"1628","1505":"1505","St. Amands, Grandon Underwood, Wiltshire, England":"Hispaania","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Broadwater, Sussex, England":"Broadwater, Sussex, England","England":"England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1487–1533":"1487–1533","1480–1533":"1480–1533","1505–1522":"1505–1522","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1505–1599":"1505–1599","1510–1628":"1510–1628","1453–1508":"1453–1508","1455–Female":"1455–Kuollut","12 Jun 1508":"12. kesäkuuta 1508","1480":"1480","about 1505":"noin 1505","1533":"1533","1599":"1599","1522":"1522","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","about 1504":"noin 1504","1453":"1453","1508":"1508","1628":"1628","1505":"1505","St. Amands, Grandon Underwood, Wiltshire, England":"Espanja","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt